  "prompt": "After finishing urination, when I walk one drop of urine comes out. I don't know why. How do I cure this problem?",
  "response": "It's not uncommon to experience a few drops of urine after finishing urination, a condition known as **post-void dribbling** or **after-dribble**. This can happen due to various reasons, including:\n\n### **Possible Causes:**\n1. **Weak Pelvic Floor Muscles:** These muscles support the bladder and urethra. If they are weak, they may not contract fully to empty the bladder completely.\n2. **An Enlarged Prostate (in men):** An enlarged prostate can put pressure on the urethra, preventing the bladder from emptying fully.\n3. **Urinary Tract Infections (UTIs):** Infections can irritate the bladder and urethra, leading to incomplete emptying.\n4. **Overactive Bladder (OAB):** This condition can cause the bladder to contract involuntarily, leading to leakage.\n5. **Nerve Issues:** Conditions like diabetes or neurological disorders can affect bladder control.\n6. **Structural Abnormalities:** Issues like a urethral stricture or prolapse can cause incomplete emptying.\n\n### **What You Can Do:**\n1. **Perform Kegel Exercises:** Strengthen your pelvic floor muscles by practicing Kegel exercises regularly. These exercises can help improve bladder control.\n   - To do Kegels: Tighten the muscles you use to stop urination (pelvic floor muscles) for 5 seconds, then relax. Repeat 10\u201315 times, 3 times a day.\n2. **Double Void:** After urinating, wait a few moments, then try to urinate again to ensure your bladder is completely empty.\n3. **Wipe or Gently Press:** After urinating, use a tissue to gently press or wipe the area to remove any residual urine.\n4. **Stay Hydrated but Avoid Bladder Irritants:** Drink plenty of water, but limit caffeine, alcohol, and spicy foods, which can irritate the bladder.\n5. **Consult a Doctor:** If the problem persists, see a healthcare provider. They may:\n   - Test for infections or prostate issues.\n   - Recommend physical therapy for pelvic floor muscles.\n   - Prescribe medications or suggest surgical options if necessary.\n\n### **When to Seek Medical Help:**\n- If you experience pain, burning, or blood in your urine.\n- If the dribbling worsens or significantly affects your daily life.\n- If you notice other symptoms like frequent urination, difficulty starting urination, or a weak urine stream.\n\nThis issue is often treatable with lifestyle changes, exercises, or medical intervention. Don\u2019t hesitate to seek professional advice for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
